{{Infobox scientist |name = Jenő Egerváry |image = Jenő_Egerváry.jpg |image_size = 150px |birth_date = {{birth date|1891|4|16}} |birth_place = [[Debrecen]], [[Kingdom of Hungary|Hungary]] |death_date = {{death date|1958|11|30}} |death_place = [[Budapest]], [[People's Republic of Hungary|Hungary]] |nationality = Hungarian |fields = [[Mathematician]] |alma_mater = [[Eötvös Loránd University|University of Pázmány Péter]] |doctoral_advisor = [[Lipót Fejér|Leopold Fejér]] |known_for = [[Kőnig–Egerváry theorem]] |awards = [[Gyula Kőnig Prize]] (1932), [[Kossuth Prize]] (1949) }} '''Jenő Egerváry''' (or '''Eugene Egerváry''') (April 16, 1891 – November 30, 1958) was a [[Hungarians|Hungarian]] [[mathematician]].
==Biography== Egerváry was born in [[Debrecen]] in 1891. In 1914, he received his doctorate at the [[Eötvös Loránd University|Pázmány Péter University]] in Budapest, where he studied under the supervision of [[Lipót Fejér]]. He then worked as an assistant at the Seismological Observatory in Budapest, and since 1918 as a professor at the Superior Industrial School in Budapest. In 1938 he was appointed [[Privatdozent]] at the Pázmány Péter University in Budapest.{{sfn|Rózsa|1984}}
In 1941 he became full professor at the [[Technical University of Budapest]], and in 1950 he was appointed Chairman of the Scientific Council of the [[Alfréd Rényi Institute of Mathematics|Research Institute for Applied Mathematics]] of the [[Hungarian Academy of Sciences]].{{sfn|Horváth|2005}}
Egerváry received the [[Gyula Kőnig]] Prize in 1932 and the [[Kossuth Prize]] in 1949 and 1953.{{sfn|Horváth|2005}}
He committed suicide in 1958 because of the troubles caused to him by the communist bureaucracy.<ref name='Spedicato'>{{cite journal |title=Ricordo di Egerváry |journal=Notiziario dell'Unione Matematica Italiana |date=November 2008 |first=Emilio |last=Spedicato |coauthors= |language=Italian |volume= |issue= |pages= |id= |url=http://umi.dm.unibo.it/old/italiano/Editoria/NUMI2008/novembre08.pdf |format= |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120330021707/http://umi.dm.unibo.it/old/italiano/Editoria/NUMI2008/novembre08.pdf |archivedate=2012-03-30 |df= }}</ref>
==Works== Egerváry's interests spanned the [[theory of equations|theory of algebraic equations]], [[geometry]], [[differential equation]]s, and [[Matrix (mathematics)|matrix theory]].{{sfn|Rózsa|1984}}
In what later became a classic result in the field of [[combinatorial optimization]],<ref name='Schrijver'>{{cite book | last = Schrijver | first = Alexander | authorlink = Alexander Schrijver | coauthors = | title = Combinatorial Optimization – Polyhedra and Efficiency | publisher = Springer | year = 2003 | location = | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = 978-3-540-44389-6 }}</ref> Egerváry generalized [[Kőnig's theorem (graph theory)|Kőnig's theorem]] to the case of [[Graph (discrete mathematics)#Weighted graph|weighted graphs]].<ref name="Egervary1931"> {{Citation|first=Jenő|last=Egerváry|year=1931|title=Matrixok kombinatorius tulajdonságairól|language=Hungarian|trans-title=On combinatorial properties of matrices|journal=Matematikai és Fizikai Lapok|volume=38|pages=16–28}} </ref> This contribution was translated and published in 1955 by [[Harold W. Kuhn]],<ref name="Kuhn1955a">{{citation|first=Harold W.|last=Kuhn|year=1955|title=On combinatorial properties of matrices|journal=Logistics Papers|publisher=George Washington University|volume=11|pages=1–11}}</ref> who also showed how to apply [[Dénes Kőnig|Kőnig]]'s and Egerváry's method to solve the [[assignment problem]]; the resulting algorithm has since been known as the "[[Hungarian method]]".<ref name="Kuhn1955b">{{Citation|first=Harold W.|last=Kuhn|year=1955|title=The Hungarian Method for the assignment problem|journal=Naval Research Logistics Quarterly|volume=2|pages=83–97|doi=10.1002/nav.3800020109}}</ref> <!-- ===Egerváry's Theorem=== Let <math>G=(V,E)</math> be a [[graph]] and let <math>w \in \mathbb{Z}^E_+</math>. A ''w-vertex cover'' is a vector <math>y \in \mathbb{Z}^V_+</math> such that <math>y_u+y_v \ge w_e</math> for every edge <math>(u,v)</math> of <math>G</math>. The ''size'' of a vector is the sum of its components.
Egerváry's Theorem can now be stated as follows. In any bipartite graph <math>G</math> with weight function <math>w:E \to \mathbb{Z}^E_+</math>, the maximum weight of a matching is equal to the minimum size of a ''w''-vertex cover. -->
