itchik]] (1882–1957), number theory and recreational mathematics<ref>{{cite book|title=An Introduction to Cryptography|last=Mollin|first=Richard A.|page=199|publisher=Chapman & Hall|year=2001|url=https://books.google.co.il/books?id=MsxSygPO_fwC|isbn=1-58488-127-5}}</ref> * [[Leopold Kronecker]] (1823–1891), number theory<ref name=james/> * [[Joseph Kruskal]] (1928–2010), graph theory and statistics<ref name=kruskal>{{cite journal|last=Brown|first=Richard D.|title=Two Baltic Families Who Came to America: The Jacobsons and the Kruskals, 1870–1970|url=http://americanjewisharchives.org/publications/journal/PDF/1972_24_01_00_brown.pdf|work=American Jewish Archives|date=April 1972}}</ref> * [[Martin David Kruskal|Martin Kruskal]] (1925–2006), mathematician and physicist<ref name=kruskal/> * [[William Kruskal]] (1919–2005), non-parametric statistics<ref name=kruskal/> * [[Kazimierz Kuratowski]] (1896–1980), mathematics and logic<ref name=jinfo/> * [[Simon Kuznets]] (1901–1985), statistician and economist; Nobel Prize in Economics (1971)<ref>{{ cite web |last = Weyl|first=E. Glen |year = 2007 |title = Simon Kuznets: Cautious Empiricist of the Eastern European Jewish Diaspora|url = http://home.uchicago.edu/weyl/Kuznets_Final_11_10.pdf |page = 8 |format = PDF |publisher = Harvard University Society of Fellows; Toulouse School of Economics |access-date = 2012-02-04 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131017201504/http://home.uchicago.edu/weyl/Kuznets_Final_11_10.pdf |archive-date = 2013-10-17}}</ref>
