{{DEFAULTSORT:Jewish Mathematicians}} [[Category:Jewish scientists| ]] [[Category:Lists of Jews|Mathematicians]] [[Category:Lists of mathematicians]]

In algebra, '''local criterion for flatness''' gives conditions one can check to show [[flat module|flatness of a module]].<ref>{{harvnb|Matsumura|loc=Ch. 8, § 22.}}</ref>
==Statement== Given a commutative ring ''A'', an ideal ''I'' and an ''A''-module ''M'', suppose either *''A'' is a [[Noetherian ring]] and ''M'' is [[idealwise separated]] for ''I'': for every ideal <math>\mathfrak{a}</math>, <math>\bigcap_{n \ge 1} I^n(\mathfrak{a} \otimes M) = 0</math> (for example, this is the case when ''A'' is a Noetherian [[local ring]], ''I'' its [[maximal ideal]] and ''M'' finitely generated), or *''I'' is [[nilpotent]]. Then the following are equivalent:<ref>{{harvnb|Matsumura|loc=Theorem 22.3.}}</ref> {{Ordered list |''M'' is a [[flat module]]. |<math>M/I</math> is flat over <math>A/I</math> and <math>\operatorname{Tor}_1^A(A/I, M) = 0</math>. |For each <math>n \ge 0</math>, <math>M_n = M/I^{n+1} M</math> is flat over <math>A_n = A/I^{n+1}</math>. |In the notations of 3., <math>M_0</math> is <math>A_0</math>-flat and the natural <math>\operatorname{gr}_I A</math>-module surjection :<math>\operatorname{gr}_I A \otimes_{A_0} M_0 \to \operatorname{gr}_I M</math> is an isomorphism.}}
The assumption that “''A'' is a Noetherian ring” is used to invoke the [[Artin–Rees lemma]] and can be weakened; see {{harv|Fujiwara–Gabber–Kato|loc=Proposition 2.2.1.}}
== Proof == Following SGA 1, Exposé IV, we first prove a few lemmas, which are interesting themselves. (See also this [https://amathew.wordpress.com/2009/12/31/flatness-and-the-local-and-infinitesimal-criteria/ blog post] by Akhil Mathew for a proof of a special case.)
{{math_theorem|name=Lemma 1|Let <math>A</math> be a ring and <math>M</math> a module over it. If <math>\operatorname{Tor}_1^A(A/I^n, M) = 0</math> for every <math>n > 0</math>, then the natural grade-preserving surjection :<math>\operatorname{gr}_I(A) \otimes_{A_0} M_0 \to \operatorname{gr}_I M</math> is an isomorphism. (See Lemma 3 below for a partial converse.)}}
''Proof'': The assumption implies that <math>I^n \otimes M = I^n M</math> and so, since tensor product commutes with base extension, :<math>\operatorname{gr}_I(A) \otimes_{A_0} M_0 = \oplus_0^{\infty} (I^n)_0 \otimes_{A_0} M_0 = \oplus_0^{\infty} (I^n \otimes_A M)_0 = \oplus_0^{\infty} (I^n M)_0 = \operatorname{gr}_I M</math>. <math>\square</math>
{{math_theorem|name=Lemma 2|Given a ring homomorphism <math>A \to B</math> and an <math>A</math>-module <math>M</math>, the following are equivalent. # For every <math>B</math>-module <math>X</math>, <math>\operatorname{Tor}_1^A(X, M) = 0.</math> # <math>M \otimes_A B</math> is <math>B</math>-flat and <math>\operatorname{Tor}_1^A(B, M) = 0.</math> Moreover, if <math>B = A/I</math>, the above two are equivalent to {{ordered list|start=3|<math>\operatorname{Tor}_1^A(X, M) = 0</math> for every <math>A</math>-module <math>X</math> killed by some power of <math>I</math>.}} }}
''Proof'': To see the equivalence of the first two, study [[Tor spectral sequence]]. (Editorial note: give more details after adding the discussion of the Tor spectral sequence to Wikipedia.) To see the "Moreover" part, if 1. is valid, then <math>\operatorname{Tor}_1^A(I^n X/I^{n+1}X, M) = 0</math> and so :<math>\operatorname{Tor}_1^A(I^{n+1} X, M) \to \operatorname{Tor}_1^A(I^n X, M) \to 0.</math> By descending induction, this implies 3. The converse is trivial. <math>\square</math>
{{math_theorem|name=Lemma 3|For each module <math>M</math> over a ring <math>A</math> and a nilpotent ideal <math>I</math>, :<math>M</math> is flat if and only if <math>M_0</math> is flat over <math>A_0</math> and <math>\operatorname{gr}_I A \otimes_{A_0} M_0 \to \operatorname{gr}_I M</math> is an isomorphism.}}
''Proof'': In view of Lemma 1, the only converse needs to be shown. Let <math>\alpha_i</math> denote the exact sequence <math>0 \to \operatorname{Tor}_1^A(A/I^i, M) \to I^i \otimes M \to I^i M \to 0</math> and <math>\gamma_i: 0 \to 0 \to I^i/I^{i+1} \otimes M \overset{\simeq} \to I^i M/I^{i+1} M \to 0</math>. Consider the exact sequence of complexes: :<math>\alpha_{i+1} \to \alpha_i \to \gamma_i.</math> Then <math>\operatorname{Tor}_1^A(A/I^i, M) = 0, i > 0</math> (it is so for large <math>i</math> and then use descending induction). 3. of Lemma 2 then implies that <math>M</math> is flat. <math>\square</math>
''Proof of the main statement''.
<math>2. \Rightarrow 1.</math>: If <math>I</math> is nilpotent, then, by Lemma 2, <math>\operatorname{Tor}_1^A(-, M) = 0</math> and <math>M</math> is flat over <math>A</math>. Thus, assume that the first assumption is valid. Let <math>\mathfrak{a} \subset A</math> be an ideal and we shall show <math>\mathfrak{a} \otimes M \to M</math> is injective. For an integer <math>k > 0</math>, consider the exact sequence :<math>0 \to \mathfrak{a}/(I^k \cap \mathfrak{a}) \to A/I^k \to A/(\mathfrak{a} + I^k) \to 0.</math> Since <math>\operatorname{Tor}_1^A(A/(\mathfrak{a} + I^k), M) = 0</math> by Lemma 2 (note: <math>I^k</math> kills <math>A/(\mathfrak{a} + I^k)</math>), tensoring the above with <math>M</math>, we get: :<math>0 \to \mathfrak{a}/(I^k \cap \mathfrak{a}) \otimes M \to A/I^k \otimes M = M/I^k M</math>. Tensoring <math>M</math> with <math>0 \to I^k \cap \mathfrak{a} \to \mathfrak{a} \to \mathfrak{a}/(I^k \cap \mathfrak{a}) \to 0</math>, we also have: :<math>(I^k \cap \mathfrak{a}) \otimes M \overset{f}\to \mathfrak{a} \otimes M \overset{g}\to \mathfrak{a}/(I^k \cap \mathfrak{a}) \otimes M \to 0.</math> We combine the two to get: :<math>(I^k \cap \mathfrak{a}) \otimes M \overset{f}\to \mathfrak{a} \otimes M \overset{g'}\to M/I^k M.</math>
Now, if <math>x</math> is in the kernel of <math>\mathfrak{a} \otimes M \to M</math>, then, a fortiori, <math>x</math> is in <math>\operatorname{ker}(g') = \operatorname{im}(f) = (I^k \cap \mathfrak{a}) \otimes M</math>. By the [[Artin–Rees lemma]], given <math>n > 0</math>, we can find <math>k > 0</math> such that <math>I^k \cap \mathfrak{a} \subset I^n \mathfrak{a}</math>. Since <math>\cap_{n \ge 1} I^n(\mathfrak{a} \otimes M) = 0</math>, we conclude <math>x = 0</math>.
<math>1. \Rightarrow 4.</math> follows from Lemma 1.
<math>4. \Rightarrow 3.</math>: Since <math>(A_n)_0 = A_0</math>, the condition 4. is still valid with <math>M, A</math> replaced by <math>M_n, A_n</math>. Then Lemma 3 says that <math>M_n</math> is flat over <math>A_n</math>.
<math>3. \Rightarrow 2.</math> Tensoring <math>0 \to I \to A \to A/I \to 0</math> with ''M'', we see <math>\operatorname{Tor}_1^A(A/I, M)</math> is the kernel of <math>I \otimes M \to M</math>. Thus, the implication is established by an argument similar to that of <math>2. \Rightarrow 1.</math><!-- TODO: give more details. --><math>\square</math>
== Miracle flatness theorem == [[Brian Conrad|B. Conrad]] calls the next theorem ''the miracle flatness theorem''.<ref>Problem 10 in http://math.stanford.edu/~conrad/papers/gpschemehw1.pdf</ref> {{math theorem|Let <math>R \to S</math> be a [[local ring homomorphism]] between local Noetherian rings. If ''S'' is flat over ''R'', then :<math>\dim S = \dim R + \dim S/\mathfrak{m}_R S</math>. Conversely, if this dimension equality holds, if ''R'' is regular and if ''S'' is Cohen–Macaulay (e.g., regular), then ''S'' is flat over ''R''.}}
